        "id": 2528291,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-11-25T15:11:30.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Since there are a few BAMA fans on the board, and since I\u2019ve just opened a bottle, I thought I\u2019d post a note on the 1982 Bel Air-Marquis d\u2019Aligre. This is a perfectly preserved example, with an upper shoulder level and a notably long cork. It\u2019s aromatically exuberant, offering up expressive aromas of blackberries, dried currants, dark chocolate, violets and cedar, with bass-notes of rich soil and asphalt emerging as it sits in the glass. On the palate, the wine is medium to full-bodied, with unusual breadth and amplitude, with a lavishly expansive and fruit-driven attack that gives way to more classical savory and sapid nuance, framed by melting tannins. While the acids are comparatively low\u2014as is so often the case with the 1982 vintage in Bordeaux\u2014the wine has lost nothing in terms of purity and vibrancy of fruit, nor does it suffer on the finish, where pronounced retronasal olfaction (that sounds even worse in French, btw) compensates for what the wine misses in acid-driven back-end follow through. This is one of the best bottles of Bel Air-Marquis that I\u2019ve drunk, the perfect foil to a rainy afternoon in Beaune, and anyone who appreciates this wine and can find a well stored bottle shouldn\u2019t hesitate.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 6,
